WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.778
I want to start with a practical question. Do we really need to recalibrate or retrain a brain-to-text decoder every day? In a B C I system this is not just theoretical.

00:00:08.828 --> 00:00:17.607
Daily calibration costs user time and requires labeled data. Our main answer is: not simply yes and not simply no.

00:00:17.657 --> 00:00:26.435
The main decoder can stay frozen, but the input state for the current day must be chosen carefully.

00:00:26.485 --> 00:00:34.673
Daily recalibration can become a user burden. Every calibration block is time the user spends maintaining the system instead of communicating.

00:00:34.723 --> 00:00:42.910
Supervised updates also require known prompts or labels at the start of the day. So the practical question is not only whether we can retrain.

00:00:42.960 --> 00:00:51.148
The question is whether we can keep the decoder fixed and manage the input state instead.

00:00:51.198 --> 00:00:58.311
This reframes the daily problem.

00:00:58.361 --> 00:01:05.474
Instead of asking: how do we train the model again today, we first ask: which historical input state is compatible with today's brain signal?

00:01:05.524 --> 00:01:12.638
The project does not propose a new speech decoder. It studies how to maintain an existing decoder by selecting the right day-specific input layer.

00:01:12.688 --> 00:01:20.092
The model we study is the public T fifteen brain-to-text G R U. The G R U backbone and phoneme output head stay frozen.

00:01:20.142 --> 00:01:27.546
What changes across days is the neural activity entering the model. The input state is the day-specific input layer, or adapter.

00:01:27.596 --> 00:01:35.001
It maps today's neural features into the representation expected by the frozen decoder.

00:01:35.051 --> 00:01:41.649
The first result shows why input-state choice matters. With the correct native-day input layer, decoding reaches about nine point zero six percent P E R.

00:01:41.699 --> 00:01:48.297
P E R means phoneme error rate; lower is better.

00:01:48.347 --> 00:01:54.945
But when sessions are forced through a wrong non-native input layer, P E R jumps to roughly twenty two to thirty four percent.

00:01:54.995 --> 00:02:01.593
The frozen decoder is not necessarily broken. The interface into it is wrong.

00:02:01.643 --> 00:02:08.418
We then asked whether the drift is just a simple mean or scale shift in individual channels.

00:02:08.468 --> 00:02:15.242
Moment matching corrects channel means and variances, but it stays near twenty one point eight two percent P E R.

00:02:15.292 --> 00:02:22.066
Input-layer calibration with twenty labeled trials helps, reaching eighteen point three eight percent.

00:02:22.116 --> 00:02:28.891
But it remains far from native-day performance, so labels help, but they should not always be the first move.

00:02:28.941 --> 00:02:37.342
The strongest low-cost move is to select a compatible input state from history.

00:02:37.392 --> 00:02:45.793
In the K equals twenty beginning-of-day setting, reusing the previous input state reaches twelve point two one percent P E R.

00:02:45.843 --> 00:02:54.244
Geometry-based retrieval is close, at twelve point seven four percent. This leads to the core ladder: reuse previous, retrieve by geometry, and calibrate only if needed.

00:02:54.294 --> 00:03:03.041
Neural geometry means the shape of the neural activity. The data has trials, time bins, and neural features.

00:03:03.091 --> 00:03:11.839
We flatten trials and time so that each time bin becomes one point in a high-dimensional channel space. A session becomes a cloud of points.

00:03:11.889 --> 00:03:20.636
Covariance summarizes how channels move together. If today's cloud resembles a past day, that past input state may still be compatible.

00:03:20.686 --> 00:03:28.210
This figure summarizes the method. At the start of a new day, a short K-shot window estimates target-session geometry.

00:03:28.260 --> 00:03:35.783
For geometry retrieval, no sentence labels are needed.

00:03:35.833 --> 00:03:43.357
The system compares the new session to stored input states, then chooses the cheapest reliable action: reuse the previous state, retrieve an older compatible candidate, or calibrate the input layer only.

00:03:43.407 --> 00:03:50.930
Throughout this process, the G R U backbone and phoneme head remain frozen.

00:03:50.980 --> 00:04:00.451
The geometry results show that drift is structured, not random. Nearby days are often nearby in geometry, creating a diagonal band in the drift map.

00:04:00.501 --> 00:04:09.972
As the number of days between source and target increases, covariance shift also tends to increase, with Spearman rho around zero point eight five in T fifteen.

00:04:10.022 --> 00:04:19.492
This explains why yesterday is such a strong baseline, while still leaving room for older states in non-monotonic cases.

00:04:19.542 --> 00:04:26.577
But geometry is not a complete policy by itself.

00:04:26.627 --> 00:04:33.662
With K equals twenty, geometry selected the previous source in twenty six sessions and an older non-previous source in eleven sessions.

00:04:33.712 --> 00:04:40.747
Among those eleven older choices, the older state actually won only three times. Previous still won seven times, and one case was tied.

00:04:40.797 --> 00:04:47.831
Geometry should propose candidates and warn about risk, not blindly override recency.

00:04:47.881 --> 00:04:55.832
The operational policy is simple. If the previous state is recent, reuse it.

00:04:55.882 --> 00:05:03.833
For zero to three day gaps, previous-state reuse is near native, around nine point nine seven percent P E R.

00:05:03.883 --> 00:05:11.834
If the previous state is stale, use geometry to inspect older candidates. If no stored state appears reliable, then perform input-layer calibration as an escalation.

00:05:11.884 --> 00:05:22.047
So the answer is not to recalibrate by ritual. Cross-session drift can be framed as input-state management. Reuse when memory is reliable. Retrieve when geometry warns.

00:05:22.097 --> 00:05:32.261
Calibrate only when evidence demands it. The decoder can stay frozen. What needs to adapt is the input state. Thank you.

